w his erotic coming of age shaped him not only as a man but also as an author. Oz reflects on his parents, his formative years on a kibbutz, and how he dealt with and learned from his critics, his students, and his fame. He talks about why there is more humor in his later books and gives his exceptional take on fear of death.Resonating with Oz’s clear, honest, and humorous voice, What Makes an Apple? offers unique insights about Oz’s artistic and personal evolution, and enables readers to explore his work in new ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Israeliy20th centuryvInterviews. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aA. B. Yehoshua.  aAbortion.  aAmos Oz.  aArabs.  aBattle of Borodino.  aBiblical Hebrew.  aBnei Brak.  aBohemianism.  aChutzpah.  aCoercion.  aContraction (grammar).  aCripple.  aCursive.  aDiaper.  aEnthusiasm.  aEtgar Keret.  aFarce.  aFemininity.  aFranz Kafka.  aFurniture.  aGeorge Bernard Shaw.  aGiza.  aGranary.  aGreater Israel.  aHalf-truth.  aHumiliation.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIdiot.  aIncome.  aInfantilization.  aIsraelis.  aKibbutz.  aLunch.  aMadame Bovary.  aMark Twain.  aMarket stall.  aMasculinity.  aMezuzah.  aMind control.  aMishnaic Hebrew.  aMitzvah.  aMy Day.  aMy Michael (novel).  aNicholas de Lange.  aNipple.  aNovelist.  aObjectification.  aOp-ed.  aOpinion piece.  aOrientalism.  aPaul Gauguin.  aPity.  aPoetry.  aPrivatization.  aRevised Version.  aSculpture.  aSelf-esteem.  aSeoul.  aSeriousness.  aState of Palestine.  aSweater.  aTendril.  aThe Newspaper.  aThe Other Hand.  aTo This Day.  aVenus de Milo.  aWriting.  aYear.  aYossi Sarid.  aYour Money.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 202